  "definitions": [
    "",
    "(transitive) to see; to observe (to perceive with one’s eyes)\nVejo duas pessoas andando.I see two people walking.",
    "",
    "(intransitive) to see (to be able to see; not to be blind or blinded)\nAbriram uma escola para os que não veem.They've opened a school for those who cannot see.",
    "",
    "(figurative, transitive) to see; to understand\nVocê vê o que eu quero dizer?Do you see what I mean?",
    "",
    "(intransitive with que and a subclause) to see; to notice; to realise (to come to a conclusion)\nEu vi que todas essas pessoas querem que eu vá embora.I saw that all these people want me to go away.",
    "",
    "(intransitive with a subclause) to check (to verify some fact or condition)\nVeja se o jantar já está pronto.Check whether dinner is ready.\nFomos ver quando os meteorologistas achavam que ia chover.We went to check when the meteorologists thought it was going to rain.",
    "",
    "(transitive) to watch (to be part of the audience of a visual performance or broadcast)\nFiquei a tarde inteira vendo TV.I spent the whole afternoon watching TV.",
    "",
    "(transitive) to see; to visit\nEla veio me ver no hospital.She came to see me at the hospital.",
    "",
    "(intransitive) to pay (to face negative consequences)\nNão acredito que mataram meu pai. Eles vão ver.I can’t believe they killed my father. They’ll pay.",
    "",
    "(takes a reflexive pronoun, copulative or auxiliary with a verb in the gerund or past participle) to find oneself (to be in a given situation, especially unexpectedly)\nApós meses gastando sem parar, João se viu enterrado em dívidas.After months spending non-stop, John found himself buried in debt.",
    "",
    "(informal, ditransitive, with the indirect object taking para or an indirect objective pronoun) to get used when ordering something from a waiter or attendant\nPor favor, me vê 500g de queijo.I would like 500g of cheese, please.(literally, “Please, see me 500g of cheese.”)\nMandei o recepcionista ver um táxi para o meu pai.I told the receptionist to get a cab for my dad.",
    "",
    "(intransitive, or transitive with com) to check with (to consult [someone] for information)\nVeja com a secretária se já enviaram o document.Check with the secretary whether the document has been sent."
  ],
  "description": "ver (first-person singular present indicative vejo, past participle visto)",
  "etymology": "From Old Portuguese veer, from Latin vidēre, present active infinitive of videō (“to see”), from Proto-Italic *widēō (“to see”), from Proto-Indo-European *weyd- (“to know; see”).",
  "page_id": 5653,
  "pronunciations": [
    "(Portugal) IPA(key): /ˈveɾ/",
